[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:treap-structure/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In computer science, a **Cartesian tree** is a binary tree derived from a sequence of distinct numbers.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] To construct the Cartesian tree, set its root to be the minimum number in the sequence, and recursively construct its left and right subtrees from the subsequences before and after this number.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] It is uniquely defined as a min-heap whose symmetric (in-order) traversal returns the original sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees were introduced by Vuillemin (1980) in the context of geometric range searching data structures.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] They have also been used in the definition of the treap and randomized binary search tree data structures for binary search problems, in comparison sort algorithms that perform efficiently on nearly-sorted inputs, and as the basis for pattern matching algorithms.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] A Cartesian tree for a sequence can be constructed in linear time.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees are defined using binary trees, which are a form of rooted tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] To construct the Cartesian tree for a given sequence of distinct numbers, set its root to be the minimum number in the sequence, and recursively construct its left and right subtrees from the subsequences before and after this number, respectively.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] As a base case, when one of these subsequences is empty, there is no left or right child.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] It is also possible to characterize the Cartesian tree directly rather than recursively, using its ordering properties.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In any tree, the *subtree* rooted at any node consists of all other nodes that can reach it by repeatedly following parent pointers.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] A symmetric (in-order) traversal of the tree results in the original sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Equivalently, for each node, the numbers in its left subtree are earlier than it in the sequence, and the numbers in the right subtree are later.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The tree has the min-heap property: the parent of any non-root node has a smaller value than the node itself.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] These two definitions are equivalent: the tree defined recursively as described above is the unique tree that has the properties listed above.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] If a sequence of numbers contains repetitions, a Cartesian tree can be determined for it by following a consistent tie-breaking rule before applying the above construction.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] For instance, the first of two equal elements can be treated as the smaller of the two.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees were introduced and named by Vuillemin (1980), who used them as an example of the interaction between geometric combinatorics and the design and analysis of data structures.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In particular, Vuillemin used these structures to analyze the average-case complexity of concatenation and splitting operations on binary search trees.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Vuillemin described both this geometric version of the structure, and the definition here in which a Cartesian tree is defined from a sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Using sequences instead of point coordinates provides a more general setting that allows the Cartesian tree to be applied to non-geometric problems as well.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] A Cartesian tree can be constructed in linear time from its input sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] One method is to process the sequence values in left-to-right order, maintaining the Cartesian tree of the nodes processed so far, in a structure that allows both upwards and downwards traversal of the tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] To process each new value a , start at the node representing the value prior to a in the sequence and follow the path from this node to the root of the tree until finding a value b smaller than a .
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The node a becomes the right child of b , and the previous right child of b becomes the new left child of a .
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The total time for this procedure is linear, because the time spent searching for the parent b of each new node a can be charged against the number of nodes that are removed from the rightmost path in the tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] An alternative linear-time construction algorithm is based on the all nearest smaller values problem.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In the input sequence, define the *left neighbor* of a value a to be the value that occurs prior to a , is smaller than a , and is closer in position to a than any other smaller value.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The *right neighbor* is defined symmetrically.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The sequence of left neighbors can be found by an algorithm that maintains a stack containing a subsequence of the input.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] For each new sequence value a , the stack is popped until it is empty or its top element is smaller than a , and then a is pushed onto the stack.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The left neighbor of a is the top element at the time a is pushed.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The right neighbors can be found by applying the same stack algorithm to the reverse of the sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The parent of a in the Cartesian tree is either the left neighbor of a or the right neighbor of a , whichever exists and has a larger value.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The left and right neighbors can also be constructed efficiently by parallel algorithms, making this formulation useful in efficient parallel algorithms for Cartesian tree construction.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Another linear-time algorithm for Cartesian tree construction is based on divide-and-conquer.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The algorithm recursively constructs the tree on each half of the input, and then merges the two trees.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The merger process involves only the nodes on the left and right *spines* of these trees: the left spine is the path obtained by following left child edges from the root until reaching a node with no left child, and the right spine is defined symmetrically.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] As with any path in a min-heap, both spines have their values in sorted order, from the smallest value at their root to their largest value at the end of the path.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] To merge the two trees, apply a merge algorithm to the right spine of the left tree and the left spine of the right tree, replacing these two paths in two trees by a single path that contains the same nodes.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In the merged path, the successor in the sorted order of each node from the left tree is placed in its right child, and the successor of each node from the right tree is placed in its left child, the same position that was previously used for its successor in the spine.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The left children of nodes from the left tree and right children of nodes from the right tree remain unchanged.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The algorithm is parallelizable since on each level of recursion, each of the two sub-problems can be computed in parallel, and the merging operation can be efficiently parallelized as well.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] This element is then removed from the list, and attached as the right child of its left neighbor, or the left child of its right neighbor, depending on which of the two neighbors has a larger value, breaking ties arbitrarily.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] This process can be implemented in a single left-to-right pass of the input, and it is easy to see that each element can gain at most one left-, and at most one right child, and that the resulting binary tree is a Cartesian tree of the input sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] It is possible to maintain the Cartesian tree of a dynamic input, subject to insertions of elements and lazy deletion of elements, in logarithmic amortized time per operation.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Here, lazy deletion means that a deletion operation is performed by marking an element in the tree as being a deleted element, but not actually removing it from the tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] When the number of marked elements reaches a constant fraction of the size of the whole tree, it is rebuilt, keeping only its unmarked elements.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Cartesian trees form part of an efficient data structure for range minimum queries.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] An input to this kind of query specifies a contiguous subsequence of the original sequence; the query output should be the minimum value in this subsequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In a Cartesian tree, this minimum value can be found at the lowest common ancestor of the leftmost and rightmost values in the subsequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] For instance, in the subsequence (12,10,20,15,18) of the example sequence, the minimum value of the subsequence (10) forms the lowest common ancestor of the leftmost and rightmost values (12 and 18).
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Because lowest common ancestors can be found in constant time per query, using a data structure that takes linear space to store and can be constructed in linear time, the same bounds hold for the range minimization problem.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Bender & Farach-Colton (2000) reversed this relationship between the two data structure problems by showing that data structures for range minimization could also be used for finding lowest common ancestors.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Their data structure associates with each node of the tree its distance from the root, and constructs a sequence of these distances in the order of an Euler tour of the (edge-doubled) tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] It then constructs a range minimization data structure for the resulting sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The lowest common ancestor of any two vertices in the given tree can be found as the minimum distance appearing in the interval between the initial positions of these two vertices in the sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Bender and Farach-Colton also provide a method for range minimization that can be used for the sequences resulting from this transformation, which have the special property that adjacent sequence values differ by one.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The same range minimization problem may also be given an alternative interpretation in terms of two dimensional range searching.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] A collection of finitely many points in the Cartesian plane can be used to form a Cartesian tree, by sorting the points by their x -coordinates and using the y -coordinates in this order as the sequence of values from which this tree is formed.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In this way, after the leftmost and rightmost points in the slab are identified, all points within the three-sided region can be listed in constant time per point.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The same construction, of lowest common ancestors in a Cartesian tree, makes it possible to construct a data structure with linear space that allows the distances between pairs of points in any ultrametric space to be queried in constant time per query.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The distance within an ultrametric is the same as the minimax path weight in the minimum spanning tree of the metric.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] From the minimum spanning tree, one can construct a Cartesian tree, the root node of which represents the heaviest edge of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Removing this edge partitions the minimum spanning tree into two subtrees, and Cartesian trees recursively constructed for these two subtrees form the children of the root node of the Cartesian tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The leaves of the Cartesian tree represent points of the metric space, and the lowest common ancestor of two leaves in the Cartesian tree is the heaviest edge between those two points in the minimum spanning tree, which has weight equal to the distance between the two points.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Once the minimum spanning tree has been found and its edge weights sorted, the Cartesian tree can be constructed in linear time.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The Cartesian tree of a sorted sequence is just a path graph, rooted at its leftmost endpoint.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Binary searching in this tree degenerates to sequential search in the path.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] However, a different construction uses Cartesian trees to generate binary search trees of logarithmic depth from sorted sequences of values.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] This can be done by generating *priority* numbers for each value, and using the sequence of priorities to generate a Cartesian tree.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] This construction may equivalently be viewed in the geometric framework described above, in which the x -coordinates of a set of points are the values in a sorted sequence and the y -coordinates are their priorities.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] This idea was applied by Seidel & Aragon (1996), who suggested the use of random numbers as priorities.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The self-balancing binary search tree resulting from this random choice is called a treap, due to its combination of binary search tree and min-heap features.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Random binary search trees have been studied for much longer than treaps, and are known to behave well as search trees.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The expected length of the search path to any given value is at most $2\ln n$ , and the whole tree has logarithmic depth (its maximum root-to-leaf distance) with high probability.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] More formally, there exists a constant C such that the depth is $\leq C\ln n$ with probability tending to one as the number of nodes tends to infinity.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The same good behavior carries over to treaps.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] It is also possible, as suggested by Aragon and Seidel, to reprioritize frequently-accessed nodes, causing them to move towards the root of the treap and speeding up future accesses for the same keys.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Levcopoulos & Petersson (1989) describe a sorting algorithm based on Cartesian trees.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] They describe the algorithm as based on a tree with the maximum at the root, but it can be modified straightforwardly to support a Cartesian tree with the convention that the minimum value is at the root.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] For consistency, it is this modified version of the algorithm that is described below.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The Levcopoulos–Petersson algorithm can be viewed as a version of selection sort or heap sort that maintains a priority queue of candidate minima, and that at each step finds and removes the minimum value in this queue, moving this value to the end of an output sequence.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] In their algorithm, the priority queue consists only of elements whose parent in the Cartesian tree has already been found and removed.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] As Levcopoulos and Petersson show, for input sequences that are already nearly sorted, the size of the priority queue will remain small, allowing this method to take advantage of the nearly-sorted input and run more quickly.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] They also prove a lower bound stating that, for any n and (non-constant) k , any comparison-based sorting algorithm must use $\Omega (n\log k)$ comparisons for some inputs.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] The problem of *Cartesian tree matching* has been defined as a generalized form of string matching in which one seeks a substring (or in some cases, a subsequence) of a given string that has a Cartesian tree of the same form as a given pattern.
[src:treap-structure/cartesian-tree] Fast algorithms for variations of the problem with a single pattern or multiple patterns have been developed, as well as data structures analogous to the suffix tree and other text indexing structures.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] In computer science, the **treap** and the **randomized binary search tree** are two closely related forms of binary search tree data structures that maintain a dynamic set of ordered keys and allow binary searches among the keys.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The treap was first described by Raimund Seidel and Cecilia R.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Aragon in 1989; its name is a portmanteau of tree and heap.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] It is a Cartesian tree in which each key is given a (randomly chosen) numeric priority.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] As with any binary search tree, the inorder traversal order of the nodes is the same as the sorted order of the keys.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The structure of the tree is determined by the requirement that it be heap-ordered: that is, the priority number for any non-leaf node must be greater than or equal to the priority of its children.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Thus, as with Cartesian trees more generally, the root node is the maximum-priority node, and its left and right subtrees are formed in the same manner from the subsequences of the sorted order to the left and right of that node.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] An equivalent way of describing the treap is that it could be formed by inserting the nodes highest priority-first into a binary search tree without doing any rebalancing.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Because random binary search trees are known to have logarithmic height with high probability, the same is true for treaps.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] This mirrors the binary search tree argument that quicksort runs in expected $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] If binary search trees are solutions to the dynamic problem version of sorting, then Treaps correspond specifically to dynamic quicksort where priorities guide pivot choices.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Aragon and Seidel also suggest assigning higher priorities to frequently accessed nodes, for instance by a process that, on each access, chooses a random number and replaces the priority of the node with that number if it is higher than the previous priority.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] This modification would cause the tree to lose its random shape; instead, frequently accessed nodes would be more likely to be near the root of the tree, causing searches for them to be faster.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Naor and Nissim describe an application in maintaining authorization certificates in public-key cryptosystems.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] In addition to the single-element insert, delete and lookup operations, several fast "bulk" operations have been defined on treaps: union, intersection and set difference.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] These rely on two helper operations, *split* and *join*.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The union of two treaps *t*1 and *t*2, representing sets A and B is a treap *t* that represents *A* ∪ *B*.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Here, *split* is presumed to return two trees: one holding the keys less than its input key, one holding the greater keys.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The algorithm for intersection is similar, but requires the *join* helper routine.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The complexity of each of union, intersection and difference is *O*(*m* log ⁠*n*/*m*⁠) for treaps of sizes m and n, with *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Moreover, since the recursive calls to union are independent of each other, they can be executed in parallel.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Split and Union call Join but do not deal with the balancing criteria of treaps directly, such an implementation is usually called the "join-based" implementation.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Note that if hash values of keys are used as priorities and structurally equal nodes are merged already at construction, then each merged node will be a unique representation of a set of keys.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Provided that there can only be one simultaneous root node representing a given set of keys, two sets can be tested for equality by pointer comparison, which is constant in time.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] This technique can be used to enhance the merge algorithms to perform fast also when the difference between two sets is small.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] If input sets are equal, the union and intersection functions could break immediately returning one of the input sets as result, while the difference function should return the empty set.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Let d be the size of the symmetric difference.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The modified merge algorithms will then also be bounded by *O*(*d* log ⁠*n*/*d*⁠).
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The numbers of descendants are used by the algorithm to calculate the necessary probabilities for the random choices at each step.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Placing *x* at the root of a subtree may be performed either as in the treap by inserting it at a leaf and then rotating it upwards, or by an alternative algorithm described by Martínez and Roura that splits the subtree into two pieces to be used as the left and right children of the new node.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] That is because the subtrees to be joined are on average at depth Θ(log n); joining two trees of size n and m needs Θ(log(n+m)) random choices on average.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] If the left or right subtree of the node to be deleted is empty, the join operation is trivial; otherwise, the left or right child of the deleted node is selected as the new subtree root with probability proportional to its number of descendants, and the join proceeds recursively.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] However, in any case, the differences between the theoretical model of perfect random choices used to design the algorithm and the capabilities of actual random number generators are vanishingly small.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Although the treap and the randomized binary search tree both have the same random distribution of tree shapes after each update, the history of modifications to the trees performed by these two data structures over a sequence of insertion and deletion operations may be different.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] For instance, in a treap, if the three numbers 1, 2, and 3 are inserted in the order 1, 3, 2, and then the number 2 is deleted, the remaining two nodes will have the same parent-child relationship that they did prior to the insertion of the middle number.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] In a randomized binary search tree, the tree after the deletion is equally likely to be either of the two possible trees on its two nodes, independently of what the tree looked like prior to the insertion of the middle number.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The idea behind an implicit treap is to use the array index as a key, but to not store it explicitly.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Otherwise, an update (insertion/deletion) would result in changes of the keys in $O(n)$ nodes of the tree.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] The key value (**implicit key)** of a node T is the number of nodes less than that node plus one.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Note that such nodes can be present not only in its left subtree but also in left subtrees of its ancestors P, if T is in the right subtree of P.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Therefore we can quickly calculate the implicit key of the current node as we perform an operation by accumulating the sum of all nodes as we descend the tree.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Note that this sum does not change when we visit the left subtree but it will increase by $cnt(T\rightarrow L)+1$ when we visit the right subtree.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] To insert an element at position *pos* we divide the array into two subsections *[0...pos-1]* and *[pos..sz]* by calling the ***split*** function and we get two trees $T1$ and $T2$ .
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Then we merge $T1$ with the new node by calling the ***join*** function.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] Finally we call the join function to merge $T1$ and $T2$ .
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] We find the element to be deleted and perform a join on its children L and R.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] We then replace the element to be deleted with the tree that resulted from the join operation.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] To show that the subtree of a given node needs to be reversed for each node we will create an extra boolean field R and set its value to true.
[src:treap-structure/randomized-binary-search-tree] To propagate this change we will swap the children of the node and set R to true for all of them.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] In discrete mathematics, **tree rotation** is an operation on a binary tree that changes the structure without interfering with the order of the elements.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] A tree rotation moves one node up in the tree and one node down.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] It is used to change the shape of the tree, and in particular to decrease its height by moving smaller subtrees down and larger subtrees up, resulting in improved performance of many tree operations.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] There exists an inconsistency in different descriptions as to the definition of the **direction of rotations**.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] This article takes the approach of the directional movement of the rotating node.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The right rotation operation as shown in the adjacent image is performed with *Q* as the root and hence is a right rotation on, or rooted at, *Q*.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] This operation results in a rotation of the tree in the clockwise direction.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The inverse operation is the left rotation, which results in a movement in a counter-clockwise direction (the left rotation shown above is rooted at *P*).
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The key to understanding how a rotation functions is to understand its constraints.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] In particular the order of the leaves of the tree (when read left to right for example) cannot change (another way to think of it is that the order that the leaves would be visited in an in-order traversal must be the same after the operation as before).
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Another constraint is the main property of a binary search tree, namely that all nodes in the right subtree are greater than the parent and all nodes in the left subtree are less than the parent.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Notice that the right child of a left child of the root of a sub-tree (for example node B in the diagram for the tree rooted at Q) can become the left child of the root, that itself becomes the right child of the "new" root in the rotated sub-tree, without violating either of those constraints.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] As seen in the diagram, the order of the leaves doesn't change.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The opposite operation also preserves the order and is the second kind of rotation.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Assuming this is a binary search tree, as stated above, the elements must be interpreted as variables that can be compared to each other.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The alphabetic characters to the left are used as placeholders for these variables.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] In the animation to the right, capital alphabetic characters are used as variable placeholders while lowercase Greek letters are placeholders for an entire set of variables.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The circles represent individual nodes and the triangles represent subtrees.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Each subtree could be empty, consist of a single node, or consist of any number of nodes.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] When a subtree is rotated, the subtree side upon which it is rotated increases its height by one node while the other subtree decreases its height.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] This makes tree rotations useful for rebalancing a tree.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Consider the terminology of **Root** for the parent node of the subtrees to rotate, **Pivot** for the node which will become the new parent node, **RS** for the side of rotation and **OS** for the opposite side of rotation.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] For the root Q in the diagram above, **RS** is C and **OS** is P.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The programmer must also make sure that the root's parent points to the pivot after the rotation.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Also, the programmer should note that this operation may result in a new root for the entire tree and take care to update pointers accordingly.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The tree rotation renders the inorder traversal of the binary tree invariant.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] This implies the order of the elements is not affected when a rotation is performed in any part of the tree.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Computing one from the other is very simple.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] There are also *double rotations*, which are combinations of left and right rotations.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] A *double left* rotation at X can be defined to be a right rotation at the right child of X followed by a left rotation at X; similarly, a *double right* rotation at X can be defined to be a left rotation at the left child of X followed by a right rotation at X.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Tree rotations are used in a number of tree data structures such as AVL trees, red–black trees, WAVL trees, splay trees, and treaps.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] They require only constant time because they are *local* transformations: they only operate on 5 nodes, and need not examine the rest of the tree.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] A tree can be rebalanced using rotations.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] After a rotation, the side of the rotation increases its height by 1 whilst the side opposite the rotation decreases its height similarly.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Therefore, one can strategically apply rotations to nodes whose left child and right child differ in height by more than 1.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Self-balancing binary search trees apply this operation automatically.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] A type of tree which uses this rebalancing technique is the AVL tree.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Can the rotation distance between two binary trees be computed in polynomial time?
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] The rotation distance between any two binary trees with the same number of nodes is the minimum number of rotations needed to transform one into the other.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] With this distance, the set of *n*-node binary trees becomes a metric space: the distance is symmetric, positive when given two different trees, and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] It is an open problem whether there exists a polynomial time algorithm for calculating rotation distance, though several variants of the rotation distance problem admit polynomial time algorithms.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Daniel Sleator, Robert Tarjan and William Thurston showed that the rotation distance between any two *n*-node trees (for *n* ≥ 11) is at most 2*n* − 6, and that some pairs of trees are this far apart as soon as *n* is sufficiently large.
[src:treap-structure/tree-rotation] Lionel Pournin showed that, in fact, such pairs exist whenever *n* ≥ 11.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The **zip tree** was introduced as a variant of random binary search tree by Robert Tarjan, Caleb Levy, and Stephen Timmel.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Zip trees are similar to max treaps except ranks are generated through a geometric distribution and maintain their max-heap property during insertions and deletions through unzipping and zipping rather than tree rotations.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Nodes of the tree contain a distinct, comparable key and a numeric rank.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The tree is max heap ordered with respect to the ranks with ties broken in favor of smaller keys.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Nodes of the tree must contain distinct keys but allow for duplicate ranks.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The rank tie-breaker favoring smaller keys creates a bias in the tree favoring smaller nodes.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] A slightly modified zip tree variant, zip-zip trees address this bias by introducing a different tie-breaker with a second rank.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Zip trees support the operations of a binary search tree.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The main implementation differences come through the zip tree's implementation of insert and delete through unzipping and zipping paths to maintain the heap ordering of the tree.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The time it takes to insert or delete a node *u* is equal to the time to search for *u* plus the time for unzipping or zipping.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The time it takes to unzip or zip is proportional to one plus the number of nodes on the path(s) being unzipped/zipped.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The expected depth of any node in a zip tree is at most 1.5 log *n*, making the expected running time of the insert, delete, and search operations all *O(*log *n)*.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] When inserting a node *x* into a zip tree, first generate a new rank from a geometric distribution with a probability of success of 1/2.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Let *x.key* be the key of the node *x*, and let *x.rank* be the rank of the node *x*.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Then, follow the search path for *x* in the tree until finding a node *u* such that *u.rank* *<= x.rank* and *u.key < x.key*.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Continue along the search path for *x*, "unzipping" every node *v* passed by placing them either in path *P* if *v.key < x.key*, or path *Q* if *v.key > x.key*.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Keys must be unique so if at any point *v.key = x.key*, the search stops and no new node is inserted.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Once the search for *x* is complete, *x* is inserted in place of the node *u.* The top node of the path *P* becomes the left child of *x* and the top node of *Q* becomes the right child.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The parent and child pointers between *u* and *u.parent* will be updated accordingly with *x*, and if *u* was previously the root node, *x* becomes the new root.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] When deleting a node *x*, first search the tree to find it.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] If no node is found with the same key as *x.key*, no deletion occurs.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Once *x* is found, continue two searches down the left and right subtrees of *x*, "zipping" together the right spine of the left subtree and left spine of the right subtree into one path *R* in decreasing order by rank.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] While creating this path top-down, nodes are added as left and right children of their parent accordingly based on their keys.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] Once the path *R* is complete, the root of the path will replace *x*.
[src:treap-structure/zip-tree] The parent and child pointers between *x* and *x*.*parent* are updated accordingly, and if *x* was previously the root node, the top node of *R* is the new root.
